Senate President Ahmad Lawan yesterday said he has all it takes to succeed President Muhammadu Buhari. He said: “I am equipped. I have experience enough, I have what it takes to be President after President Muhammadu Buhari leaves office,” Lawan said in Minna, Niger State, while addressing the All Progressives Congress (APC) delegates from the state. Lawan and his campaign team met Governor Abubakar Sani Bello, delegates to the forthcoming presidential primaries and later paid homage to the Emir of Minna, Dr. Umar Farouq Bahago.   Uneasy calm in Niger APC     Emefiele withdraws suit against INEC, AGF     Emir of Damaturu to Osinbajo: we pray you succeed   Lawan, according to a statement by his Special Adviser (Media), Ola Awoniyi, solicited the votes of the delegates against the background of what he had to offer, his vast experience in governance and the stability he had brought to the parliament. Governor Bello thanked the Senate President and his team for the visit. He said: “I think he has laid out his plans for Niger State for you delegates to consider, so that you give him your mandate to represent our party at the next presidential election. “I don’t need to say much. You all heard when he started. He has been in the National Assembly since 1999. I don’t think anyone has broken that record yet in Nigeria.”